          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;">
          <strong>
          Calcium and Magnesium – The Supporters</strong></p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;">
          With age, your bones decline in density and turn into a porous Swiss cheese. This condition is called osteoporosis.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Magnesium is like a manager that helps calcium do its job. It supports calcium to build strong bones and activates vitamin D to make sure calcium works properly.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;">
          This team slows down the weakening of bones, making them strong enough to be unaffected by fractures.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;">
          <strong>
          Potassium – The Reliever</strong></p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;">
          Ever heard your grandparents complain about joint pain? This is because they have lost some fluid in their joints, which causes arthritis.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;filter:blur(5px);">
          Potassium helps in balancing those fluids, relieves pain and also helps support stiff joints by working with muscles. So they don't have to suffer alone.</p>
